6. What is a reference datatype? Give examples?
-->In Java, a reference data type is a type of variable that stores the address (reference) of an object, not the actual value.

      👉 The actual data is stored in heap memory, and the variable holds a reference pointing to it.
      
      📌 Example:
      String name = "Karthikeya";
      name → stores reference (address)
      "Karthikeya" → stored in heap memory
      ✅ Examples of Reference Data Types
      Class
      Student s = new Student();
      String
      String str = "Hello";
      Array
      int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
      Interface
      Runnable r;
      🔁 Key Points
      Store reference (address), not actual data
      Stored in heap memory
      Can be null
      Created using new keyword (mostly)
      🎯 Simple Understanding
      
      👉 Primitive → stores value
      👉 Reference → stores address of value
      
      📝 Short Exam Answer
      
      A reference data type in Java stores the memory address of an object rather than the actual value. Examples include String, arrays,
      classes, and interfaces.


7. Can primitive datatypes hold null? Can reference datatypes hold null?
-->In Java, whether a data type can hold a null value depends on whether it is a primitive or a reference type. 
    Primitive Data Types: No, primitive data types cannot hold null. According to the Oracle Java Tutorials, the null literal cannot be assigned to
    variables of primitive types. Primitives such as int, boolean, and double must always hold a concrete value, falling back to predefined default 
    values (like 0 or false) if they are uninitialized.

    Reference Data Types: Yes, reference data types can hold null. As explained by W3Schools, reference types (such as String, Array, or any class
    instance) store memory addresses rather than actual data. A value of null indicates that the reference variable does not point to any object 
    in memory. 


8. What is the difference between primitive and reference datatypes?
-->
| Feature         | Primitive Data Types              | Reference Data Types                |
| --------------- | --------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| Definition      | Store actual value                | Store reference (address) of object |
| Memory Location | Stack                             | Heap (data) + Stack (reference)     |
| Data Stored     | Direct value                      | Address of object                   |
| Examples        | `int`, `float`, `char`, `boolean` | `String`, arrays, classes           |
| Size            | Fixed                             | Depends on object                   |
| Default Value   | 0, 0.0, false, '\u0000'           | null                                |
| Performance     | Faster                            | Slightly slower                     |
| Null Allowed    | ❌ No                              | ✅ Yes                               |
| Created Using   | Direct assignment                 | `new` keyword (mostly)              |



9. Can a variable be declared without assigning a value? What happens if you try to use it?
-->1. Local Variables (Inside a Method)
    If you declare a variable inside a method, it is a local variable. 
    Behavior: Java does not assign default values to local variables.
    What happens if you use it: If you try to use an uninitialized local variable, the compiler will throw a compile-time error stating that the variable might not have been initialized.
    Example:
    java
    void myMethod() {
        int x; // Declared but not assigned
        System.out.println(x); // COMPILE-TIME ERROR: variable x might not have been initialized
    }

    2. Class-Level Variables (Instance or Static)
    Variables declared directly within a class (outside methods) are fields. 
    Behavior: Java automatically assigns a default value to these variables based on their data type.
    What happens if you use it: You can use them immediately without explicit initialization, and the program will run using the default value.
    Common Default Values:
    int, byte, short, long: 0
    float, double: 0.0
    boolean: false
    char: '\u0000' (null character)
    Object References (e.g., String): null




10. Can primitive datatypes be declared inside constructors, static blocks, instance blocks, or non-static methods? Explain.
-->Yes — primitive data types can be declared anywhere inside a class, including constructors, static blocks, instance blocks, and methods in Java.
    
    👉 Because primitives are just normal variables, they follow the same scope rules.
    
    ✅ 1. Inside Constructor
    
    ✔️ Allowed — they act as local variables
    
    class Demo {
        Demo() {
            int x = 10;  // primitive inside constructor
            System.out.println("Constructor value: " + x);
        }
    }
    ✅ 2. Inside Static Block
    
    ✔️ Allowed — used during class loading
    
    class Demo {
        static {
            int x = 20;  // primitive inside static block
            System.out.println("Static block value: " + x);
        }
    }
    ✅ 3. Inside Instance Block
    
    ✔️ Allowed — runs when object is created
    
    class Demo {
        {
            int x = 30;  // primitive inside instance block
            System.out.println("Instance block value: " + x);
        }
    }
    ✅ 4. Inside Non-Static Method
    
    ✔️ Allowed — most common usage
    
    class Demo {
        void display() {
            int x = 40;  // primitive inside method
            System.out.println("Method value: " + x);
        }
    }
    🔥 Important Note
    
    👉 All these variables are local variables, so:
    
    Stored in stack memory
    No default values (must be initialized before use)
    🎯 Final Answer (Exam Ready)
    
    Yes, primitive data types can be declared inside constructors, static blocks, instance blocks, and methods. In all these cases, they behave as
      local variables and must be initialized before use.




11. If you declare all primitive datatypes inside a method and try to print them without initialization, what happens?
-->If you declare primitive datatypes inside a method (as local variables) and attempt to print them without initialization, the program will fail to compile. 
    According to the Java Language Specification, the following happens:
    Compiler Error: The Java compiler will throw a "variable might not have been initialized" error.
    No Default Values: Unlike class-level (instance or static) variables, local variables are not automatically assigned default values like 0 or false.
    Mandatory Initialization: You must explicitly assign a value to a local variable before it is accessed in any operation, including printing
    with System.out.println().
    Safe Declaration: Simply declaring the variables without using them is allowed and will not cause an error; the error only triggers when you try
    to use (read) the uninitialized variable.


12. What happens if you declare a primitive variable with a value larger than its range? Give an example.
-->In Java, if you assign a value larger than the allowed range of a primitive data type, you’ll get a compile-time error (in most direct assignments).
    
    🔹 Case 1: Direct Assignment (Compile-Time Error)
    byte b = 130;   // ❌ Error
    
    👉 Why?
    
    byte range = -128 to 127
    130 is outside the range
    
    ✔️ Result: Compilation fails
    
    🔹 Case 2: With Explicit Casting (Overflow Happens)
    byte b = (byte)130;
    System.out.println(b);
    
    👉 Output:
    
    -126
    ⚠️ Why this happens?
    Java cuts extra bits (overflow)
    It wraps around using 2’s complement
    🔹 Another Example
    int x = (int)2147483648L;
    System.out.println(x);
    
    👉 Output:
    
    -2147483648
    🎯 Key Concept
    
    👉 If value exceeds range:
    
    Without casting → ❌ Compile-time error
    With casting → ⚠️ Overflow (wrong/rotated value)
    🧠 Easy Understanding
    
    Think like a clock ⏰:
    
    Max reached → it starts again from minimum
    👉 This is called overflow
    📝 Short Exam Answer
    
    If a primitive variable is assigned a value beyond its range, Java gives a compile-time error. If explicitly cast, the value overflows 
    and produces an incorrect result due to wrap-around.




